    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Judges' Campaign Fray</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas O'Brien letter, commenting on Oct 7 article, says election of judges by lawmakers is preferable to their direct popular election</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Court Rulings Curb Efforts to Rein In Judicial Races'' (news article, Oct. 7):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Court Rulings Curb Efforts to Rein In Judicial Races'' (news article, Oct. 7):</p>
        <p>Judicial campaign fund-raising creates grave conflicts of interest. Electing judges by popular vote also prevents strong candidates from seeking judgeships, because they must forfeit stable law practices.</p>
        <p>Yet another problem with popular elections is that uninformed voters must make decisions on the basis of 30-second attack ads focusing on a small sample of the candidate's record. By contrast, election by legislatures ensures informed voting by lawmakers familiar with the candidate's record.</p>
        <p>Leaving the informed decisions in their hands would eliminate the mudslinging and deceptive attack ads that sully the process. It also avoids the First Amendment questions of regulating campaign speech in popular judicial elections.</p>
        <p>THOMAS O'BRIEN  Charlottesville, Va., Oct. 9, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a public policy analyst.</p>
      </block>
